    ```javascript
function canArrange(arr, k) {
    let counts = new Array(k).fill(0);
    for (let num of arr) {
        counts[(num % k + k) % k]++;
    }
    if (counts[0] % 2 != 0) {
        return false;
    }
    for (let i = 1; i <= k / 2; i++) {
        if (counts[i] !== counts[k - i]) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}
```

    1. Create a counts array of size k, initializing all elements to 0.
2. Iterate through the input array and increment the count of (num % k + k) % k (to handle negative numbers as well) for each element in the array.
3. After counting, if the count at index 0 (sums that are multiples of k) is not even, return false, since we cannot create n / 2 pairs.
4. Iterate through the counts array from index 1 to k / 2 (inclusive) and check if the counts at index i and (k - i) are equal, if not then return false, since pairs cannot be formed that sum up to a multiple of k.
5. If no issues are found, return true as the pairs can be formed.

